               <note>Fiey provides the following bibliographic citations: <quote source="#bibl1163-1">Voir Ia Vie de Barsaum, avec ses 99 ou 100 miracles, ecrite vers 55Q--61, dans Nau, "Resume" (1913, 1914). Version ethiopienne: S. Grebaut, ROC 13 (1908), et 14 (1909) . DHGE, s.v. Barsauma 1, VI, col. 946- 47 (G. Bardy). BS, II, 842 (J .-M. Sauget). V. surtout : Honigmann, Bar$aumii, 6- 23 ; H. Kaufhold, dans Hugoye 3 (2000).</quote>
               </note>
               <note type="abstract">BARṢAUMA was the head of mourners at a monastery near Melitene; he was a disciple of Abraham of the high mountain.  He was a rigid monk who chased the Jews out of Jerusalem and a friend of Dioscorus of Alexandria, leader at the Robber Council of 449.  He mobilized his monks to rehabilitate Eutyches. He condemned the priest Flavian at the Council of Chalcedon and was expelled at the Council of Chalcedon. </note>
